nlmInfo.value: The Schrödinger model uses 3 quantum numbers ({{n}},{{l}},{{m}}) to describe the most probable location of an electron, also known as an orbital.

mInfo.value: {{m}}, the Magnetic Quantum Number, describes the orientation of the orbital in space.

playArea.value: There is a light source aimed at a sample of hydrogen atoms. The observation window displays a zoomed-in view of a single atom, which varies with the mode of exploration. In Model mode, there are various quantum models of the hydrogen atom to explore. In Experiment mode, the atom’s structure is a mystery and is obscured. Determine the structure of the hydrogen atom by shining white or monochromatic light on the sample. Observe changes in the electron’s state in the Electron Energy Level diagram.

controlArea.value: There is a Spectrometer that displays a histogram of the photons emitted by the hydrogen atom. Take snapshots of the spectrometer to compare data.
